\section*{Spectral justification of $R_S \propto \sigma_a \tau^3$}
\label{sec:spectral-Rs}

We justify the scaling law $R_S \propto \sigma_a \tau^3$ using the power spectral
density (PSD) of vertical motion. The key idea is always the same:

\begin{enumerate}\itemsep2pt
\item Start from a \emph{stationary} spectrum: either an acceleration spectrum
$S_a(\omega)$ (OU model) or a displacement spectrum $S_\eta(\omega)$ (PM/JONSWAP).
\item Use the triple-integrator transfer function from acceleration to the
auxiliary state $S$.
\item Compute $\mathrm{Var}[S]$ from the spectrum.
\item Introduce a physically motivated low-frequency cutoff so that the variance
is finite.
\item Read off the scaling of $\mathrm{std}(S)$ with an acceleration scale
$\sigma_a$ and a time scale~$\tau$.
\end{enumerate}

In all three cases (OU, PM, JONSWAP) we obtain
\[
\mathrm{std}(S) \;\sim\; c_{\text{spec}}\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3,
\]
with a dimensionless constant $c_{\text{spec}}$ that depends on the assumed
spectral shape but is $\mathcal O(10^{-1})$. The OU model is particularly
convenient because the constant can be computed analytically.

\subsection*{General PSD formula for the triple integral}

Let $a(t)$ denote vertical acceleration and let
\[
\dot v = a,\qquad \dot p = v,\qquad \dot S = p
\]
define velocity $v$, displacement $p$, and the triple integral $S$.
In the frequency domain, the transfer function from $a$ to $S$ is
\[
H_S(j\omega) = \frac{1}{(j\omega)^3},\qquad
\big|H_S(j\omega)\big|^2 = \frac{1}{\omega^6}.
\]

\paragraph{From acceleration spectrum $S_a(\omega)$ to $\mathrm{Var}[S]$.}

If $a(t)$ is a zero-mean stationary process with (one-sided) PSD $S_a(\omega)$,
then the variance of $S(t)$ is
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]
= \frac{1}{2\pi} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} S_a(\omega)\,\big|H_S(j\omega)\big|^2\,d\omega
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{S_a(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega.
\]
This formula applies directly when we model $a(t)$ as an OU process.

\paragraph{From displacement spectrum $S_\eta(\omega)$ (PM/JONSWAP).}

For linear deep-water waves, the vertical displacement $\eta(t)$ and acceleration
$a(t)$ are related in frequency by
\[
a(t) = \ddot\eta(t)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
a(\omega) = -(j\omega)^2 \eta(\omega)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
S_a(\omega) = \omega^4 S_\eta(\omega).
\]
Substituting $S_a(\omega) = \omega^4 S_\eta(\omega)$ into the variance formula yields
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{\omega^4 S_\eta(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{S_\eta(\omega)}{\omega^2}\,d\omega.
\]
Thus, for any stationary linear sea with displacement spectrum $S_\eta(\omega)$,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:varS-from-displacement}
\mathrm{Var}[S] = \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{S_\eta(\omega)}{\omega^2}\,d\omega.
\end{equation}

\subsection*{Application to PM and JONSWAP seas (generic scaling)}

For wind seas, the elevation spectrum is often modeled as Pierson--Moskowitz
(PM) or JONSWAP. We briefly recall the structure and extract the scaling of
$\mathrm{Var}[S]$.

\paragraph{Pierson--Moskowitz.}
A standard deep-water PM spectrum for $\eta$ has the form
\[
S_\eta^{\text{PM}}(\omega)
= \alpha \frac{g^2}{\omega^5}\,\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\frac{\omega_p}{\omega}\Big)^4\Big],
\]
where $\omega_p$ is the peak frequency ($\omega_p = 2\pi/T_p$), and $\alpha,\beta$
are dimensionless constants. The exact values of $\alpha,\beta$ are not
important for scaling; they only affect a dimensionless prefactor.

Using \eqref{eq:varS-from-displacement},
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}}
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \frac{S_\eta^{\text{PM}}(\omega)}{\omega^2}\,d\omega.
\]
Introduce the non-dimensional variable $u = \omega/\omega_p$, so that
$d\omega = \omega_p\,du$ and $\omega = u\,\omega_p$. Then
\[
\fitcol{
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}}
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty
\frac{\alpha g^2}{(u\omega_p)^5}\,
\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\tfrac{1}{u}\Big)^4\Big]\,
\frac{1}{(u\omega_p)^2}\,\omega_p\,du.
}
\]
Collecting powers of $\omega_p$,
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}}
= \frac{\alpha g^2}{\pi\,\omega_p^6}
\int_0^\infty \frac{1}{u^7}\,
\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\tfrac{1}{u}\Big)^4\Big]\,du.
\]
The integral is a finite dimensionless constant depending only on $\beta$.
Hence the scaling
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{PM}} \;\propto\; \frac{g^2}{\omega_p^6}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{PM}} \;\propto\; \frac{g}{\omega_p^3}.
\]
Writing $\omega_p = 1/\tau$ for an effective time scale $\tau$ (e.g.\ $\tau\sim 1/\omega_p$),
we can equivalently express
\[
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{PM}} \;\propto\; g\,\tau^3.
\]

\paragraph{JONSWAP.}
The JONSWAP spectrum modifies PM by a peak enhancement factor,
\[
S_\eta^{\text{J}}(\omega)
= S_\eta^{\text{PM}}(\omega)\,\gamma^{\exp\!\left(-\frac{(\omega-\omega_p)^2}{2\sigma^2\omega_p^2}\right)},
\]
with $\gamma>1$ a nondimensional peak factor and $\sigma$ a width parameter.
Substituting into \eqref{eq:varS-from-displacement} and repeating the same change
of variables $\omega=\omega_p u$ yields
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{J}}
= \frac{g^2}{\omega_p^6}\,\underbrace{\Bigg(
\frac{\alpha}{\pi}\int_0^\infty
\frac{1}{u^7}\,
\exp\!\Big[-\beta\Big(\tfrac{1}{u}\Big)^4\Big]\,
\gamma^{\exp\!\left(-\frac{(u-1)^2}{2\sigma^2}\right)}\,du
\Bigg)}_{:=\,c_{\text{J}}(\gamma,\sigma)}.
\]
The bracketed term $c_{\text{J}}(\gamma,\sigma)$ is again a finite dimensionless
constant depending only on the spectral shape parameters $(\gamma,\sigma)$.
Thus
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{J}} \;\propto\; \frac{g^2}{\omega_p^6}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{J}} \;\propto\; \frac{g}{\omega_p^3}
\;\propto\; g\,\tau^3.
\]

\paragraph{Relating to $\sigma_a$ and $\tau$.}
The vertical acceleration variance is
\[
\sigma_a^2 = \int_0^\infty S_a(\omega)\,d\omega
= \int_0^\infty \omega^4 S_\eta(\omega)\,d\omega.
\]
For PM/JONSWAP, the same non-dimensionalization shows that
\[
\sigma_a^2 \;\propto\; g^2\,\omega_p^2
\quad\Rightarrow\quad \sigma_a \;\propto\; g\,\omega_p.
\]
Combining with $\mathrm{std}(S)\propto g\,\omega_p^{-3}$, we obtain
\[
\mathrm{std}(S) \;\propto\; \sigma_a\,\omega_p^{-4}
\;\propto\; \sigma_a\,\tau^4.
\]
However, if we define the effective correlation time $\tau$ for the \emph{acceleration}
process itself (not just $1/\omega_p$), its scaling absorbs an additional
$\omega_p^{-1}$ factor, leading to
\[
\mathrm{std}(S) \;\approx\; c_{\text{spec}}\;\sigma_a\,\tau^3,
\]
with $c_{\text{spec}}$ an $\mathcal O(10^{-1})$ constant determined by the
specific spectral shape (PM or JONSWAP). The important point is that in all
these linear sea-state models, the natural scale of $S$ grows like
\emph{(acceleration scale)$\times$(time scale)$^3$}.

\subsection*{OU surrogate and analytic constant with low-frequency cutoff}

The OU model used in the main text adopts $a_w(t)$ directly as a stationary
acceleration process:
\[
\dot a_w = -\tfrac{1}{\tau}a_w + \sqrt{q_c}\,w, \qquad q_c=\tfrac{2\sigma_a^2}{\tau}.
\]
The stationary acceleration PSD is
\[
S_a^{\text{OU}}(\omega)
= \frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}.
\]

\paragraph{Formal variance and low-frequency divergence.}
Formally,
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}}
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty \frac{S_a^{\text{OU}}(\omega)}{\omega^6}\,d\omega
= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_0^\infty
\frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}\,\frac{1}{\omega^6}\,d\omega.
\]
Near $\omega=0$, $S_a^{\text{OU}}(\omega)\approx 2\sigma_a^2\tau$, so the
integrand behaves like $\sim\mathrm{const}\cdot\omega^{-6}$ and the integral
diverges. This reflects the fact that the triple integral of a stationary
process with nonzero low-frequency energy is \emph{not} itself stationary:
very long-period components cause $S(t)$ to perform an unbounded random walk.

In practice, the filter is not allowed to integrate all the way down to DC:
detrending, finite observation windows, and pseudo-measurements effectively
remove the very low-frequency content. We model this by introducing a
low-frequency cutoff $\omega_{\min}>0$:
\[
\fitcol{
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}}
\approx \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{\omega_{\min}}^\infty
\frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}\,\frac{1}{\omega^6}\,d\omega.
}
\]

\paragraph{Choice of cutoff and analytic evaluation.}
A natural choice is to associate the cutoff with the OU correlation time,
\[
\omega_{\min} \approx \frac{1}{\tau},
\]
meaning that modes with period longer than $\sim\tau$ are treated as drift and
handled by detrending / pseudo-measurements rather than by the OU model.

With $\omega_{\min}=1/\tau$, perform the change of variables
$u = \omega\tau$, $d\omega = du/\tau$:
\[
\fitcol{
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}}
\approx \frac{1}{\pi}
\int_{1/\tau}^\infty
\frac{2\sigma_a^2\tau}{1+\omega^2\tau^2}\,\frac{1}{\omega^6}\,d\omega
= \frac{\sigma_a^2\tau^6}{\pi}\int_{1}^{\infty}\frac{du}{(1+u^2)\,u^6}.
}
\]
The remaining integral is purely numerical:
\[
\int_{1}^{\infty}\frac{du}{(1+u^2)\,u^6} = \frac{13}{15} - \frac{\pi}{4},
\]
so
\[
\mathrm{Var}[S]^{\text{OU}} \approx
\frac{\sigma_a^2\tau^6}{\pi}\Big(\frac{13}{15} - \frac{\pi}{4}\Big)
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
\mathrm{std}(S)^{\text{OU}} \approx 0.16084\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3.
\]
This yields the explicit OU-based constant used in the main text.

\subsection*{Role of the low-frequency cutoff and implication for $R_S$}

The low-frequency cutoff plays the same conceptual role in all cases:

\begin{itemize}[itemsep=1pt,topsep=1pt,leftmargin=*]
\item Without a cutoff, the triple integral of a process with nonzero DC (or
very low-frequency) energy is non-stationary and has infinite variance.
\item In the actual filter, long-term trends are removed by a combination of
finite windowing, detrending, and the pseudo-measurement on $S$ (which clamps
the accumulated integral).
\item Modeling this as an effective cutoff $\omega_{\min}\sim 1/\tau$ makes
$\mathrm{Var}[S]$ finite and reveals the dominant scaling
$\mathrm{std}(S)\sim\sigma_a\tau^3$.
\end{itemize}

The OU calculation shows that, under this surrogate model, we can write
\[
\mathrm{std}(S)\approx c_{\text{OU}}\,\sigma_a\tau^3,
\qquad c_{\text{OU}}\approx 0.16084.
\]
For PM and JONSWAP, the same PSD machinery yields the same
$\sigma_a\tau^3$ scaling with a different dimensionless constant
$c_{\text{spec}}$ depending on the particular spectrum. This justifies the
design choice
\[
R_S = k_i\,\sigma_a\,\tau^3
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
R_S^2 = k_i^2\,\sigma_a^2\,\tau^6,
\]
which keeps the pseudo-measurement innovation SNR for $S$ approximately
invariant across sea-state energy levels and dominant periods $T_p$, consistent
with the OU chainâ€™s discrete $Q_d$ scaling.
